(166, 'news', 106, NULL, 0, 'en', NULL, 'Russia & China To Start Youth Exchange Program. ', 'Russia and China will send 10,000 students to each other’s countries, to strengthen international relations as part of the Youth Friendly Exchanges Year.', 'As the world looks to China in awe, the middle kingdom itself is strengthening ties with its immediate neighbours.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn fact, Russia and China will send 10,000 students to each other’s countries, to strengthen international relations as part of the Youth Friendly Exchanges Year.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nChinese Vice Premier Liu Yandong said:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n"We will launch a youth exchange program that involves 100 schools and 10,000 students from each country.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n"We will earnestly plan and prepare for the opening ceremony of the youth year to be held in Russia next spring<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLiu feels there is an opportunity to increase friendly cooperation and further the China-Russia strategic partnership.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition, one million students will be able to engage online with the hope of increasing the numbers of Chinese-Russian translation students.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, the two countries will work together at the Sochi Winter Olympic Games and send young athletes to the sixth China-Russia Youth Games as well.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOther countries including India and the UK are looking at forming relationships with China, undoubtedly highlighting the global influence the country has. Of course the communist history shared with Russia and China will play a large part in the ways they move forward socially, economically and politically.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<div>\r\n	<br />\r\n</div>', 1329408000),
(167, 'news', 106, NULL, 0, 'en', NULL, 'UK transport official wants stronger links with China.', 'Patrick McLoughlin, the UK’s secretary of state for transport wants stronger ties with China in terms of transportation and the airline industry.', 'The UK’s secretary of state, Patrick McLoughlin, has put forward an interest in creating stronger links with China in terms of transportation and the airline industry.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMcLoughlin visited China for 5 days on a trip to learn more about the high-speed rail system. The possibility of increasing air travel frequencies between the two countries is also on the agenda.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMcLoughlin said:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n“China has developed its high-speed trains quickly and successfully. Obviously, China is a country of a massively bigger scale than the UK, but the connection of major cities and the transportation link is very important (in both countries),"<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn a reversal of the norm, the UK looks to follow in the East’s footsteps by developing its own high-speed rail.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nEventually London and Birmingham will be linked, reflecting the system already implemented between Beijing and Shanghai and more. In fact, McLoughlin wants cooperation from Chinese companies in the construction of the UK railway, to begin works in 2017.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs England was the birthplace of the railway for passenger travel, it is interesting to see China being touted as a leader in the industry. It yet again reflects the emergence of China as a world leader and influence that touches all facets.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<div>\r\n	<br />\r\n</div>', 1329408000),
(168, 'news', 106, NULL, 0, 'en', NULL, 'Beijing has a new plan to fight city smog.', 'Beijing will soon be alleviated from smog and pollution, as factory closures and vehicle restrictions look set to be introduced.', 'There is no denying that at times, Beijing’s city pollution has gone beyond the occasional bout of smog. But relief to ‘choked’ citizens will be on the way, with new plans to ensure fresher air.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe government of the city says that the strictest emergency measures will be implemented when the index for particulate matter, PM 2.5, exceeds 300 micrograms per cubic meter.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe new measures will see private vehicles restricted to operation on alternative days, which will be dictated by the numbers on the license plates. The odd – even notion was used during the 2008 Olympics to great success, which saw a short lived but significant improvement in air quality.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBeijing’s factory emissions will be cut by an impressive 30% that will see the suspension and limitation on factory production. Construction sites will be forced to down tools, stop work and effectively down tools.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThese new rules will affect Beijing industry and residents only, despite more than 50% of the city’s pollution coming from Hebei, a neighbouring province.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHeavy pollution episodes should be improved by these measures and we look forward to seeing the impact.', 1329408000),
(169, 'news', 106, NULL, 0, 'en', NULL, 'Shanghai Free Trade Zone to welcome hotel boom.', 'The creation of the Free Trade Zone in Shanghai will likely introduce much needed tourists and in turn, a hotel boom in the city.', 'The launch of the Shanghai Free Trade Zone will be a massive step forward for the city and experts expect a knock-on effect, of increased hotel bookings.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe centre of Shanghai has some of the most well known hotel brands, including the Grand and Park Hyatt.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn fact, Sam Xie who is the research director at CBRE Shanghai said:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n"The demand came from both guests attending the ceremony and business owners registering companies in the free-trade zone in Waigaoqiao,"<br />\r\n<br />\r\n"There are definitely opportunities for international hoteliers, given the current limited supply and the increasing number of financial and service companies entering the zone."<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSince the announcement of the FTZ, property prices have risen by 20% compared with the 10% growth of the rest of Shanghai.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn fact, tourism in Pudong could peak at 45.2 million in 2015, which could equate to 52.3 billion Yuan in revenue.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Free Trade Zone will encourage more foreign companies to set up offices in China and also allow foreign investment. The likes of private telecom organizations, will also be allowed to compete in the zone.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is a significant step forward for the future of international investment in China, something that is essential to secure future growth and prosperity.&nbsp;<br />', 1329408000),
